A style of American country music that grew from the compositional stylings of Bill Monroe and his incredible group; the Blue Grass Boys. With roots originating from traditional British folk, bluegrass combines elements of dance, home entertainment, old- time, and religious folk music. A bluegrass band typically consists of four to seven individuals who sing and accompany themselves on acoustic string instruments. As heard in other country styles, improvisation plays a large part in Bluegrass music.

The era of traditional country didn't begin until the late '20s, when Jimmie Rodgers became the first national country music star. Following Rodgers' success, old-time music faded in popularity and traditional country was born. For the next 40 years, most country music fell under the traditional country umbrella, regardless if it was the big-band dance music of Western swing or driving roadhouse honky tonk.

The era of traditional country didn't begin until the late '20s, when Jimmie Rodgers became the first national country music star. Following Rodgers' success, old-time music faded in popularity and traditional country was born. For the next 40 years, most country music fell under the traditional country umbrella, regardless if it was the big-band dance music of Western swing or driving roadhouse honky tonk.

Americana developed as a roots-oriented reaction to the slick commercial sounds that dominated mainstream country during the decade. Much of what fell under the Americana umbrella was in fact a revival of dormant country styles, including Western swing and rockabilly. Popular Americana artists include Bob Dylan, Bruce Springsteen, and Alison Krauss.

Alternative Country (or alt-country) refers to country artists that play traditional country, americana, and bluegrass styles, but bend the rules slightly. Alternative country artists work outside of the country industry's spotlight, frequently subverting musical traditions with singer/songwriter and rock & roll lyrical (and musical) aesthetics.

The Neo-Traditional movement came as a reaction to Country Music's evolution into mainstream Pop Music. Artists involved with the Neo-Traditional Country movement believed that they were bringing country back to its roots, making the old music new again. Artists like Randy Travis, Patty Loveless, and Emmy Lou Harris aimed to stay rooted deeply in Traditional Country of the 40's, 50's, and 60's, while still being influenced by the popular music of the day.
The amalgamation of Western Swing, Honky Tonk, and Pop Music. It began with artists like George Strait and Reba McEntire and continued with Alan Jackson.

Blues came from over a hundred-year-evolving juxtaposition of the musical and cultural traditions of Africa (i.e. African American slaves) and Europe. Traditional Blues represent the structural and cultural genesis of blues, a genre that manifested an array of African-American cultural experience (i.e. spirituals to work songs to field hollers) into a three-phrase lyrical prose aligned within a 12-bar song structure. The 12-bar blues song-form is musically identified by a thematic, three-chord progression which uses the tonic, sub-dominant and dominant chords of the scale and a melodically alternating, bended blue note: a lowered third scale degree (or mediant), which alternates with frequent improvisation, between its natural third scale degree. Rooted in the traditions of the Deep South and also known as Country Blues, Traditional Acoustic Blues is primarily minimal in instrumentation (i.e. a vocalist accompanied by an acoustic guitar) and lyric themes tend to focus on hardship and sorrow.

Spanning most of the Eastern seaboard -- from Delaware to Florida -- Piedmont Blues refers at once to the geographical proximity of its practitioners and to a distinct style of playing guitar. This "Piedmont style" consists of a syncopated finger- picked guitar melody that follows a ragtime-esque rhythm. Ensembles usually consist of a solo performer who both sings and plays guitar. Piedmont style can be traced back to the 1920s, though it did not gain popularity until the 1930s and early 40s. By the end of World War II, the style had fallen out of favor-- only to attain an audience once again during the 60s Folk Revival. It remained popular in black communities until the final quarter of the 20th century.

An extension of the popular Boogie Woogie sound of the time, Jump Blues served as a stepping stone to the early Rock n' Roll of the 1950s. Jump Blues combined up-tempo rhythms with small ensembles--usually comprised in part by a brass section. Somewhat harder-edged than their Boogie Woogie forebears, Jump Blues musicians combined grittier instrumentation with playful lyrics.

With geographical origins reaching deep into the Southern United States and musical ingredients inherited from ragtime and the blues of the Mississippi Delta, Boogie Woogie is considered by many to be a forefather of Rock n Roll and Rockabilly. Originally performed for dance and characteristically identified as a percussive and virtuosic, piano-based blues technique, Boogie Woogies musical identity is fundamentally defined by a rapid, two-handed piano conversation -- comprised of a left- handed bass (i.e. a walking or ostinato bass pattern) and a melodically-playful, often wildly-improvised, right-hand -- chronicled within a twelve-bar blues song-form.

The 1920s was witness to a Black workers' emigration from life on the Delta; Black workers left behind rural plantation life and headed into urban centers, North, West and East, which promised a higher quality of life. Both this urbanization, which shifted the geographical focus of blues away from its traditional Southern Roots, and the invention of the electric guitar (which had gained popularity in the Jazz Big Bands of 1930s) gave birth to the adoption of the electric guitar into Blues. Early Traditional Electric Blues traces include West Coast Blues guitarist T-Bone Walker (originally form Texas), who began experimenting with the electric guitar in the mid 1930s in Los Angeles. While in the 1940s, in Memphis, Memphis Minnie, Muddy Waters and Arthur "Big Boy" Crudup in Chicago, in Texas, Sam "Lightnin Hopkins and in Detroit, John Lee Hooker. Through the 1950s-1970s, Traditional Electric Blues paved the way for other genres including Rock N' Roll, R&B, Soul and Classic Rock many artists of which continued to expand the aesthetic potential of the Blues by applying more contemporary instrumentation to it, all the while upholding the essential components of Blues music in their compositions. Electric blues is a type of Traditional Blues music distinguished by the amplification of the guitar, bass guitar and often the harmonica.

One of the epicenters of Traditional Electric Blues, Chicago Blues used amplification on guitar, electric bass and harmonica. Chicago Blues has a more extended palette of notes than the standard six-note blues scale; often, notes from the major scale and dominant 9th chords are added which gives the music more of a "jazz feel" while remaining in the confines of the blues genre. Chicago blues is also known for its heavy rolling bass. Chicago Blues developed in the first half of the twentieth century due to the Migration of poor Black workers which moved from the South into the industrial cities of the North such as Chicago.

Primarily (but not exclusively) piano- and horn-driven, New Orleans Blues is enlivened by Caribbean rhythms, an unrelenting party atmosphere, and the "second-line" strut of the Dixieland music so indigenous to the area. There's a cheerful good-naturedness to the style that infuses the music with a good-time feel, no matter how somber the lyrical text. The music itself uses a distinctively "lazy" feel, with all of its somewhat complex rhythms falling just a hair behind the beat

Swamp arose from the Louisiana sound incorporating elements of zydeco, soul music and cajun. It is noticeably more laid back than other blues styles -- even its uptempo songs are reminiscent of slow blues. Utilizes simple, but effective guitar work and standard blues form.
British Blues refers to English bands that play American blues music.

Modern Gospel represents several contemporary crossover styles of Gospel-- wherein it may be combined with R&B, Urban, Rock or another genre. As such, the arrangements and instrumentation for this sub-genre may vary greatly, and include both organic and digital/synthetic ensembles.

With an emphasis on the American musics that influenced Gospel, Spirituals tend to focus on older folk-gospel songs. Given the oral tradition that allowed these songs to be passed on, they are predominantly vocal and refrain-heavy.

Ragtime is a major precursor to Jazz. Ragtime developed as a march structure which also utilizes the polyrhythm of African music. Polyrhythm is the occurrence of independent rhythms simultaneously, thus the combination of march and polyrhythm was initially referred to as "ragged-time" music.

Dixieland evolved as a combination of ragtime, march and blues. It typically features a lead instrument improvising over a rhythm section. Dixieland was the first style of jazz to be recorded. It eventually suffered from an onslaught of novelty acts which led to it's decline in popularity in the 1930's.

Jazz Blues represents a combination of Jazz and Blues styles-- usually uniting the 12-bar Blues chord progression with Jazz instrumentation and improvisational techniques. Other aspects of these genres (i.e. Blues riffs, Jazz chord sequences) are regularly employed.

Swing developed out of Ragtime and Dixieland music; however, Swing music incorporated written arrangements to better suit large ensembles (as opposed to Dixieland which relies on improvisation). In Swing, improvisation only occurs during a solo, but the soloist is inclined to show restraint. Therefore, there is a lot of repetition in Swing.

Traditional Jazz is a catchall term that encompasses several early styles of Jazz: Ragtime, Dixieland, Boogie Woogie, Charleston, among others. What unites these styles of Jazz are their roots in Blues, Folk and March music. Ragtime and Dixieland predate the musical use of the term "Jazz", which did not come to fruition until 1918. Jazz eventually became a blanket term, referring to already existing genres of music.
1930s French-Influenced Small Ensemble Swing

Bebop developed out of Swing in early 1940's. It follows a similar structure to Swing. The main difference between the two is that Bebop primarily focuses on the chord as opposed to individual melody.

Named in part for its more relaxed tempos, gentle tones and smooth harmonies, Cool Jazz evolved out of Bebop in the early 1950s. Arrangements and compositions were of great importance, occasionally hinting at classical and swing influences.

Hard Bop developed as a reaction to Cool Jazz. In many ways, Hard Bop was a return to the African- American folk sensibilities of Jazz, as opposed to Cool and West Coast Jazz which relied heavily on European music traditions. Hard Bop tends to be soulful and bluesy deviating from the softer sounds of Cool. Hard Bop came to fruition in the United States in the mid-1950's. In 1954, Miles Davis released the album, Walkin' which is said to have introduced the Hard Bop style to the world.

Infused with the radical politics of the 1960s, Free Jazz musicians strayed from chord structures, instead focusing on short themes and a near complete autonomy of improvisation. Highly experimental and usually atonal, Free Jazz constitutes one of the most controversial sub-genres in Jazz.

Modal Jazz is a style of jazz which utilizes modal structures as opposed to a specific key. The Modal structure is comprised of "modes" which are essentially one of 7 diatonic scales which alter in order of semitones (2) and halftones (5). Modal jazz paved the way for more experimental structures of jazz such as post-bop and the avant-garde.

Rather than a particular aesthetic or sound, Modern Jazz refers to a multiplicity of styles and sub-genres that emerged after the 1940s and 50s, when the then-traditional tropes of Jazz's first generations were either challenged or progressively embraced by an influx of musicians young and old.

An unusually complex and inclusive sub-genre, Post Bop has become no less narrow in its aesthetic groupings. The movement is typically viewed as an extension of Hard Bop and Bebop that utilized an array of chord changes and modalities. While these modal concerns were often harmonically inclined, they expressed a newfound freedom that would eventually blossom in Free Jazz. Post Bop impressionist proclivities allow it to move deftly between styles, grooves and modalities. It is usually performed by a small combo.

The Avantgarde functions as a reaction to the mainstream. Avantgarde Jazz incorporates improvisation with other experimental music forms uncommon to mainstream Jazz. It is similar to Free Jazz in its use of improvisation. It is different from Free Jazz in that Avantgarde Jazz usually involves a distinct structure which provides the context for the improvisation.

Modern Creative serves as a highly experimental and fusion-based take on progressive jazz. It usually applies the stylistic conceits of older jazz genres-- be it bop, free or traditional-- with more contemporary genres like rock, pop or funk. It may be structured or free, and arrangements may vary.

An antecedent of the Jazz Funk movement of the 1970s and heavily influenced by Blues, Gospel & R&B, Soul Jazz was mostly performed by organ or piano based combos and was thematically focused around deep rhythmic grooves and melodic ostinatos.

With the popularization of Funk music a sub-genre amalgamation of funk and jazz was inevitable. Jazz Funk pulls from funk, soul, R&B and Jazz-- it is a primary form of Fusion. It is one of the first styles of Jazz to incorporate synthesizers.

Acid Jazz constitutes the fusing of Jazz aesthetics and chord structures with funk and hip-hop styles. It frequently utilizes looped rhythms and other forms of electric instrumentation. Acid Jazz may be performed by a band or DJ.

Retro Swing refers to a style music in the 1990's which resuscitated Swing and Jump Blues, combining them with Rockabilly and Rock music. The band usually features a small horn section along with a typical pop/rock ensemble.

Stemming from the evolution of Fusion in the 1970s, Smooth Jazz highlighted the more polished and gentle side of the then-nascent genre. It subdues improvisation for the sake of groove and rhythm, and is usually characterized by slow tempos and flowing melodies. It utilizes electronic instruments and pulls together strands of Funk, R&B and Jazz.
Latin Jazz serves as a catchall sub-genre denoting a fusion between American Jazz styles and Latin music. Unlike traditional Jazz, Latin Jazz employs a straight rhythm and Latin instrumentation.

Afro-Cuban Jazz refers both to a Jazz-influenced Latin music that moved from Cuba to the USA in the early 20th century, and American Jazz that was in turn influenced by Latin rhythms and improvisations, either prior to or after this emigration. Afro-Cuban Jazz is also typified by Latin instrumentation and arrangements.
Extending from American and Latin Jazz traditions-- though most notably Samba-- Bossa Nova Jazz imbues complex harmonies and melodies with soft rhythms and relaxed singing.
Flamenco Fusion refers to the melding of American Jazz sensibilities with the tradition of Flamenco music, which is characterized by guitar-led ensembles and fast, improvised rhythms.

Doo Wop grafted African-American Gospel sensibilities with R&B and Rock N' Roll rhythms. "Doo Wop" describes the intricate vocal interplay in the music; smooth diatonic vocal harmonies, shouts, and rhythmic vocals both respond to and accompany the lead vocal, as it is frequently traded-off between the singers of the group
A catch-all term referring to the first several decades of R&B's existence -- during which the genre emphasized blues- like rhythms, tight and spare instrumentation, and vocal groups.
Buoyed by a usually uptempo and cheerful aesthetic, New Orleans R&B is primarily driven by piano, horn sections and vocal groups. However, it is also characterized by laid-back, swaying rhythms.

A catch-all for describing classic Soul music from the mid-1950s through to the late 1970s. In its quintessential form, soul is the union of gospel and rhythm & blues; underlying intricate, groove-oriented rhythms, surrounded by lush orchestrations and arrangements that lay the foundation for intimate and sensual vocalizations.
Chicago Soul is heavily influenced by gospel music. Lighter in approach compared to southern and country-soul, it spurred the album- oriented soul revolution of the early 1970's.
Similar in sound and aesthetic to Southern Soul with more prominent gospel-vocal influences.
Memphis Soul is a funkier soul music which describes pioneered by the artists of Memphis' Stax and Hi Records.

Southern Soul is gritty, funky soul that borrows from southern gospel and high energy rhythm and blues. It is distinguished by a gospel- tinged singer, punchy horns, chicken-scratch guitars and tight rhythm sections.

Considered to be a precursor to funk, Psychedelic Soul combines the modern technologies of the late 1960s including electronic keyboards and synthesizers, guitar effects, studio effects and production techniques similarly used in Psychedelic Rock to infuse esoteric, ambient and distorted textures into traditional soul arrangements.
R&B's answer to soft rock and adult contemporary. Primarily ballad-driven, soft, subdued and sensual anthems, Quiet Storm was inspired by the Smokey Robinson album "A Quiet Storm".
Blue-Eyed Soul is soul music performed by white artists.

Retro Soul is the carbon copy re-creation of the musically-defining ingredients of the classic era of soul typically including the replication of vintage production aesthetics instrumentation arrangements and songwriting style.

Named after the legendary Detroit record label founded by Berry Gordy, Motown was the first African-American owned label featuring African-American artists to achieve American mainstream popular success. The "Motown Sound" characterized by soft, smooth, soulful vocals over simple, straight-forward arrangements with highly memorable melodic hooks echoing throughout the instrumentation. Motown's success and distinctive sound can be attributed to the use of the same songwriters, producers, musicians and studio for every recording. Notably, the Funk Brothers, a group of highly-talented session musicians who helped defined the sound and craft of Motown's music.
A catch-all to describe unique and obscure Soul music titles produced in the 1960s in the northern United States.

Phillysound is the highly-produced and arranged soul music sound of 1970s Philadelphia. It's lush, impressive orchestrations include sweeping strings, intricate vocal interplay, horns and melodic jazz undertones. The Phillysound is the forerunner to Disco and Modern Urban and R&B.

Spawned from the 1970s socio-political, black film movement of the same name, Blaxploitation is quintessentially smooth, intimate, grove-oriented soul and funk music characterized by funky beats, congas, grooving bass and wah-wah.
R&B (modern) describes the modern fusion of soul gospel and funk with modern production techniques and technologies including sampling and synthesis.
The fusion of modern production techniques uptempo dance-influenced grooves and ostinatos combined with the sensual intimate vocals of classic soul create Dancefloor Soul.

Originally called Swingbeat New Jack Swing is the infusion of hip-hop beat-production techniques with the songwriting and sensual singing style of contemporary R&B. Producer and songwriter Teddy Riley is often credited as the founding force of the New Jack Swing sound (also early Babyface & L.A. Reid).

Neo-soul is the 1990s (to present) modern R&B re-invention of the classic soul era. It is a fusion of R&B's modern production techniques with a return to the singer-songwriter tradition and sound of the classic era of soul music. In unison with the identity of the classic soul music movement Neo-soul focuses on black American identity unity and socio-political consciousness.

Immediately following the formation of rocksteady, roots reggae is a cross between American Rock, Ska and Rocksteady. Vocals are central, typically with devout Rasta lyrics, and concerned with "truth and rights", social injustice and issues, and the legacies of colonialism.

A style of popular music that developed out of ska in the 1960's, said to be the result of the hot summer of 1966, and the need for a less energetic dance sound. It is half the speed of ska. The slower rhythm created more space for vocalists and musicians to be more creative/experimental with melody. Rocksteady paved the way for Reggae.

Though Ska is stylistically distinct, it incorporates a variety of influences: New Orleans R&B, jump blues, Jamaican mento, calypso, jazz and Jamaican folk. It developed into a sound dominated by a piano or guitar emphasis upon the back-beat which gives ska its trademark jerky liveliness. Ska itself has spawned several sub-genres including 2 Tone and Ska Punk.

Soca is a style of Caribbean Music formed in Trinidad & Tabago geared more towards dance and celebration that blends traditional Calypso and other Indian inspired music including Chutney music. Soca is characterized by a steady bass drumbeat against which a highly syncopated cymbal and snare drum pattern are juxtaposed. The basselines are also syncopated. Like other styles of modern music, today's Soca uses a recorded drum sections played by drum machines, The percussion being at the forefront of the track is sometimes the only instrument to back up the vocals. Horn sections can be present in live Soca shows which consist of two trumpets and a trombone with saxophones being part of the section at times.

Reggaeton combines Reggae and Dancehall with Latin American music styles and Hip Hop. The style features rapping or singing, usually in Spanish. Reggaeton originated in Panama and Puerto Rico in the early 1990s.

A style that evolved from youth culture in the ghettos of Kingston, Jamaica, ragga artists utilize digital instrumentation as a means of generating a greater quantity of music--often putting different melodies and lyrics atop the same rhythm track. Constructed primarily of these synthesized rhythms, Ragga ostensibly served as a cost-effective means of producing songs and albums. Ragga was influential in the evolution of the UK drum & bass scene.

Emerging from the UK, this R&B influenced, romantically themed style became popular in the mid to late 70's, especially amongst urban dwellers looking for an alternative to the more politically driven reggae music of the time.

Dub originally consisted of rhythmic instrumental B-sides on 45 rpm singles, some of which proved popular in a club environment. King Tubby was among the first to develop the style by sporadically dropping sections of the rhythm and vocal tracks from the mix while applying several effects (i.e. heavy bass, echo and reverb), intended to give the sound its spacious and deceptively minimal sound.

Dancehall is a style of Reggae music developed in the late 1970's in Jamaica. Dancehall puts more emphasis on rhythms while singers/deejays perform over pre-recorded tracks as opposed to live instrumentation during the early years of Dancehall, it wasn't until the mid 80's when producers started to introduce electronic rhythms to faster paced tracks. Lyrics are more oriented towards local dancehall audiences commenting on the dance and prowess of the singer and sound system compared to the political or Rastafarian themes of other styles of Reggae. Sexual explicit themes also known as slackness and violent themes are also increasingly common in Dancehall Reggae.
Distinguishable primarily by contemporary production techniques and sound value.

As the term implies, the Golden Age is considered to be the heyday of Hip Hop. During these years, Hip Hop transitioned from regional clusters of musically unique sub-cultures into a global, multi-platinum, mainstream musical force. Despite their success, Hip Hop artists of the Golden Age maintained their sense of roots, innovation, musical diversity, and integrity. Sampling production techniques became an essential ingredient of the genre and lyrical subject principally focused on underlying themes of black identity and socio-political consciousness. Golden Age encompasses the monumental US releases of these years including, Run-DMC's "Rising Against", Public Enemy's "It Takes A Nation Of Millions To Hold Us Back", Beastie Boys' "License To Ill" and KRS-One, Eric B. & Rakim, De La Soul, and A Tribe Call Quest.

East Coast Hip Hop is a highly influential style of Hip Hop that developed in New York City, particularly in the South Bronx, during the seventies. It's history can be traced back as far as the Hip Hop genre itself. While East Coast Hip Hops complex development and endless permutations can never be demonstrated by one particular sound, the late eighties and early nineties specifically saw a number of artists define themselves by hard-hitting, sample-heavy production, as well as lyricism with both a refined social conscience and trademark aggression. Essentially Eastcoast Rap is rap that encompasses any artists or music that originates in the easternmost region of the United States

Westcoast Rap is rap that encompasses any artist or music that originates in the westernmost region of the United States (specifically California). Though Westcoast Rap has no distinct sound, It too was a major contributor to the growth of Rap music and it's many styles like Gangsta Rap, G-Funk, Latin Rap etc...Lyrically Westcoast Rap's subject matter usually include fame, money, cars & women as well as the gangsta lifestyle and marijuana.

Party Rap is characterized as heavy bass driven, lively and positive non aggressive Rap music made strictly for dancing. Lyrical content has none of the political overtones of Hardcore Rap but does sometime contain sexual content.
Miami Bass is a form of hip hop known for an upbeat tempo and heavy throbbing Roland 808-style beats, hyperkinetic rhythms and usually sexually explicit lyrics.

Dirty Rap is is a subgenre of Hip Hop music that contains lyrical content revolving mainly around sexually suggestive subjects. The lyrics are overtly explicit and graphic, often to the point of either being cartoonish or extremely offensive. Historically dirty rap often contained a distinctly bass-driven sound which arose from the popular Miami bass rap scene.
Christian Rap is rap music that is focused on faith, praise and worship of God lyrically. Christian Rap features all conventional styles of Rap music and no one style dominates.

Originating on the West Coast through the work of Dr. Dre with Above the Law, G-Funk stood in contrast to many of the dominant Hip Hop sounds of the time. Focusing on the similarly-named P-Funk, Dr. Dre and Cold 187um created a form of Rap which sounded much more relaxed and organic than many sample-based Rap tracks. This was achieved through limiting the amount of samples in a track and dressing them up with live instrumentation. By the mid-1990s, this style would have proliferated throughout the Midwest and Southern states for a period becoming the dominant form of Hip Hop. For a number of reasons G-Funk did not appear often in the East Coast areas although artists like Redman would adopt its emphasis on funk samples.

Southern Rap unites the many musically diverse sounds throughout the urban areas of the southern United States into one sub- genres. Southern Rap weighs driving beats over lyrical content and a unifying element between the regions emphasizes deep grooving bass lines and Southern soul samples

Fond of crossing the boundaries of a particular genre Alternative Rap artists attempt to upend the traditional aesthetic of hip hop by combining it with elements of funk rock jazz or any other genre. It is typically not as popular as other genres of hip hop though it does lend itself to a crossover audience.

Often reflecting the grittiness of urban environments, Hardcore Rap maintains a tough aesthetic through both its instrumentation and lyrical content. Beats are aggressive and noisy while lyrics are similarly tough-minded and occasionally menacing. Following its inception, Hardcore Rap expanded to encompass an array of themes and styles -- from party anthems to Gangsta Rap.
Turntablism is the art of manipulating sounds and creating music from scratching or beat juggling using phonograph turntables and a DJ mixer.

Underground Rap has no distinct style but can be described as lesser known Rap groups or artist who are not promoted by major record labels often due to their experimental musicianship and lyrical content. Also many underground Artists use Rap to communicate collective consciousness, social justice and political change. The beats of Underground Rap are often characterized by the fusion of loops sampled from all genres of music including Jazz, Classical, Funk, Rock & Blues.
British Rap or Brithop is a catch-all to describe Rap music made in the United Kingdom.

Characteristically minimal while simultaneously fervent Grime is typified by the union of unpredictably synchronized breakbeats with raw mechanical synthesizer ostinatos. Generally clocking in around 140 BPM Grime is principally the fusion of Techno and Hip Hop and is also influenced by Dancehall.

Beat music constituted one of the first forms of British Pop not directly inspired by American musicians. Its most famous proponents are the Beatles, whose melodic sensibility and complex songwriting style harkened to more traditional forms of European folk music.

Influenced by American Rock n Roll and Blues, a wave of British bands found popularity in the U.S. in the mid-1960s-- thanks in no small part to the Beatles. Their sound reflected a range of styles-- from bluesy hard rock to sweet pop/rock. A second wave in the late 60s found influence in both American musicians and their British precedents.

With an emphasis on melody, harmony and clean production, Chamber Pop attempts to apply Classical aesthetics to a distinctly Pop song structure and template. Instrumentation frequently includes strings and woodwinds. Chamber Pop may also be referred to as "Baroque Pop"

Power Pop is an amalgam of pop and rock-- incorporating the energy of 1960's British rock groups with the melodies and harmonies of The Beatles. Power Pop typically features crisp catchy guitar riffs, vibrant synths, tight vocal harmonies and a strong rhythm section. Production-wise, songs are typically polished and processed.

Psychedelic Pop grew out of the Psychedelic Rock scene of the mid-60's. Where Psychedelic Rock tends to expand on the form of the pop song, Psychedelic Pop essentially remains grounded within the pop template, adding instruments and sounds associated with the Psychedelic movement (sitars, pedals, synthesizers, reversed tape, distortion).

One of Pop's most commercially viable sub-genres Teen Pop refers to Pop music that is directly produced for and marketed to teenagers. As such its lyrical themes rarely stray far from love; its melodies are purposely infectious and its production value is slick and clean.

New Age music is represented by various styles which serve to inspire relaxation and positive spiritual feelings. Its ethereal textures and circular rhythms are often used by listeners for yoga, massage, meditation, stress management, or to create a peaceful atmosphere. It is often associated with environmentalism and New Age Spirituality.

CCM stands for Contemporary Christian Music. This sub-genre contains modern popular music which is lyrically focused on matters concerned with the Christian faith. CCM is presented in a very palatable form rooted in modern Praise & Worship, Pop, and Rock, so that it can be heard on the radio as well as in church.

Britpop is an amalgam of various group from English Pop history: The Beatles, The Kinks, David Bowie, The Smiths and XTC (among a plethora of others) created music which would influence a generation of British performers. Britpop focuses on British culture and the British experience with little regard for how it is perceived outside of British Society. Although it may have been moderately popular in foreign underground music scenes, the music is/was highly commercialized in the UK.

Indie Pop has its roots in the Alternative Rock/Pop and Underground scenes of the UK and United States. Initially, the term "indie" referred to bands signed to independent record labels. Indie Pop connotes a style of music utilizing the pop music template while incorporating an aesthetic that out weighs the politics and pr of mainstream pop music. However, the term has come to represent a demographic as opposed to any sort of political or aesthetic agenda. Many Indie Pop bands are signed to major labels as popularity for the subgenre has grown, esp. in the late-90's and early-aughts of the 21st century. Indie Pop can be used as a catch-all phrase for many underground subgenres from the 1980's and 1990's, such as: Dream Pop, Post Punk, Power Pop, Twee Pop, Shoegaze, etc. Its sound is less aggressive than its sister subgenre, Indie Rock. Indie Pop often incorporates (but certainly isn't limited to) jangly guitars, sloppy riffs, ironic and/or cutesy lyrics, and lo-fi production. In many ways it has developed out of a suburban interpretation of the cool aesthetic. Currently, Indie Pop has a strong international following, with many bands coming from the UK, United States, Continental Europe, Japan, Australia, etc.

Madchester came onto British Pop scene in the mid-1980's as a fusion of British Rock, Acid House and modernized-60's Pop. The result is a pop style that relies heavily on melody and Pop structure while incorporating "baggy" beats, so that the music is dance-oriented.

Neo-Psychedelia evolved from the Psychedelic movement of the 1960's. Neo-Psychedelia is a blanket term for many styles: some taking cues from their 1960's predecessors and some going another direction incorporating elements from Punk, Post Punk, etc.

New Romantic is a more decadent, heavily produced, glam-influenced brand of New Wave. The music embodies the trends and fashions of the UK in the early 1980's. Because of it's reliance on a distinct yet fickle fashion, it was quick to die out a few years after its inception.

The term No Wave was coined as a reaction to New Wave, which was gaining mainstream momentum at the time. Although No Wave has no distinct sound-- it is associated with the underground punk and avant-garde music scenes of New York City in the late 1970's. The sound incorporates elements of jazz, funk, pop, rock and experimental music.
Taking thematic and structural queues from traditional/mainstream Pop, Noise Pop combines tropes of noise music (i.e. feedback, drones, distortion) with a melodic sensibility.

Named after the stoic, hunched performances of its early progenitors, Shoegaze describes a style of Pop that is at once introspective, dense, melodic and noisy. Heavily effected guitars are often layered to create an all-encompassing and dreamlike atmosphere

Twee Pop is a derivative of Indie Pop and therefore has its roots in the release of NME's C86 mixtape. Twee typically features a quaint, child-like vocal delivery-- there is no confrontation. It utilizes jangly guitars, low-end model keyboards, lo-fi production and innocent lyrics. Songs are typically sweet, carefree and/or cheerful/bright in sub-mood.

Disco is a genre of dance music that originated in the United States in the early to late 1970s that fuses R&B, Funk & Soul music. Unlike the simpler four-piece band sound of the funk & soul of the late 1960s, disco music often included vocalists, with several chordal instruments (guitar, keyboards, synthesizer), several drum or percussion instruments (drumkit, Latin percussion, electronic drums), a horn section, a string orchestra, and a variety of "classical" solo instruments. Not coincidentally Disco was generally a producer led genre rather than as centered as much around the artists as other genres. As a genre that introduced dj's, dance clubs, extended mixes and remixes, Disco is the true beginning and basis for all dance music

Dancefloor is a style of Electronic Dance Music and a sub-genre of Pop music that evolved from disco and combines dance beats with a Pop/R&B song structure. Because there is such an emphasis on fully-formed songs in dance-pop, it is often viewed as a separate classification unto itself apart from pure dance music. Dancefloor can be four-on-the-floor or the beats can be heavily syncopated with melodic synthesized chords. Lyric themes in Dancefloor usually deal with romance, love & partying.

Eurodance is a genre of Electronic Dance Music that originated in the early 90's primarily in Europe. It combines elements of Techno, Trance, HiNRG & Eurodisco. Most Eurodance songs are between 110-150 BPM and is characterized by euphoric synthesized melodic riffs with female vocals and occasional male rapping with catchy hooks. Eurodance also features a strong four-on-the-floor kick drum pattern and is mostly cheerful/bright in mood.

Freestyle is an Electronic Dance Music genre which fuses Latin Hip Hop and Latin Pop music with melodic vocal styles found in '70s disco music with synthesized instrumentation of the '80s Electro/Hip Hop sound. It was developed mostly in New York and Miami, and peaked in the mid to late '80s. The style is characterized by Latin percussion, heavy syncopation and themes of romance, love, and partying.

Dream Pop is an atmospheric subgenre of alternative rock that relies on sonic textures as much as melody. Dream pop often features breathy vocals and processed, echo-laden guitars and synthesizers. Though the Cocteau Twins, with their indecipherable vocals and languid soundscapes, are frequently seen as the leaders of dream pop, the genre has more stylistic diversity than their slow, electronic textures. Dream pop also encompasses the post-Velvet Underground guitar rock of Galaxie 500, as well as the loud, shimmering feedback of My Bloody Valentine. It is all tied together by a reliance on sonic texture, both in terms of instruments and vocals. fusion of post-punk, aery textures and bittersweet pop melodies with sensual, sonically spacious soundscapes. Breathy vocals and reverb/chorus-drenched instruments are typical, and lyrics are generally introspective and existential.

While Post Punk refers to a more creative, complex version of late 70's early 80's underground music-- New Wave refers to underground music of the same era that is less challenging and more accessible (therefore, more poppy).

Synth pop is a subgenre of New Wave and pop music in which the synthesizer is the dominant musical instrument. While most current popular music in the industrialized world is realized via electronic instruments, synth pop has its own stylistic tendencies which differentiate it from other music produced by the same means. Synth Pop is epitomized by the band Depeche Mode.

Derived from punk rock synth pop and new wave NDW (Neue Deutsche Welle/German New Wave) utilizes a predominantly synthetic aesthetic to engage several strains of 70s/80s pop music. Beginning as an underground scene NDW's non-traditional German sound soon found clout with a wider audience.

Nouvelle Chanson or 'New Chanson' is a recently coined buzzword used to define a new style of music emerging in France one which takes clear inspiration from the forefathers of French Chanson (including Jacques Brel Barbara and Charles Aznavour) albeit in an updated style. However the principal influences appear to be the more avant-garde artists. The defining characteristic of Chanson both old and new is that it focuses on the French language as vehicle and instrument.

Bachata is the traditional music of Dominican Republic. It combined Cuban, Puerto Rican and African music traditions and is closely related to Bolero. It is the predecessor of Merengue. It has undergone many changes to get to it's contemporary form, but in it's original incarnation it featured a lead accordion.

MPB or Music Popular Brasileira was formed in the late 60's as a modernized form of Bossa Nova and Samba-Cancao. MPB encompasses many foreign styles of popular music (i.e. rock/pop/folk/jazz) while retaining it's distinct Brazilian identity with lyrics in portuguese.
Extending from the popular Blues Rock sounds of the late 1960s, Boogie Rock placed a greater emphasis on a repetitive groove instead of improvisation.
The timeless rock format of the 1960s and 1970s. Hints of glam and psychedelia with the raw energy and palatability of 1960s Pop Rock.

Influenced by 60s and 70s Garage Rock, Americana, and Roots rock, Heartland rock is a timeless genre that has mass appeal, catchy hooks, and anthemic production. This sub-genre is epitomized by Bruce Springsteen, Tom Petty, and Bob Seger.

An incredibly broad term, Rhythm & Blues refers to an expansive history of predominantly African-American popular music; it also serves as a term whose connotations are in constant flux. Rhythm & Blues was first used to describe the highly rhythmic blues and jazz-influenced music that pre-dated Rock n Roll in the 1940s and 50s, though it would later come to more widely describe those musics that integrated the sounds of soul, funk, gospel and other genres.

Rock n Roll constitutes an early incarnation of Rock music, a genre of popular music characterized by small groups, boogie woogie blues rhythms, and often sexual lyrics. Rock n Roll had a massive social impact, influencing dance, fashion, language and other art forms, and would generate innumerable new genres over the ensuing decades.
Fusing 60s Blues Rock and Country, Southern Rock places an emphasis on electric guitar-led jams and Country-influenced melodies.

Surf came out of the surfing culture of the early 1960's. Initially it was instrumental music featuring a lead saxophone or electric guitar heavily affected by reverb (to emulate the sound of the ocean). Vocal Surf Pop followed with notable acts such as The Beach Boys and Jan & Dean. There are a variety of guitar playing techniques that are associated with surf including bending notes downward with the whammy bar and tremolo picking. It was also one of the first Pop music styles to incorporate the use of electric bass. Through use of these techniques, the reverb, and later, beach-themed lyrics, performers sought to capture the essence of surfing in musical form. Named after the sport with which it became so closely associated, Surf rock is typified by reverb-effected electric guitar, three-chord song structures, rolling drum fills, and vocal harmonies.

Oi! Began as an attempt to keep Punk music rooted in working-class/street culture. It was a simpler, harder, and faster version of Punk--aligning itself with drinking songs and football chants. Unfortunately, (due to the band "Skewdriver") the genre became closely associated with Neo-Nazism.

Riot Grrrl is a feminist punk movement closely associated with the LBGT movement, Queer Theory, and Straight Edge movements. Because of it's association with political activism, it has developed into a subculture. The music is comprised of typically loud and distorted instrumentation with a primary focus on political and social issue themed lyrics.

Screamo takes cues from Hardcore and Emo music, combining the two. The lyrics are typically overwrought and melodramatic, referring to relationships, self-deprecation and violence. The music is distorted and loud, embodying the existential angst inherent to the lyrics.

Hardcore punk (or hardcore) is an underground music genre that originated in the late 1970s, following the mainstream success of punk rock. Hardcore is generally faster, thicker, and heavier than earlier punk rock, while its vocalists usually scream, chant and use spoken word poetry. Hardcore was heavily involved with the rise of the independent record labels in the 1980s and with the DIY ethics in underground music scenes. It has influenced a number of music genres which have experienced mainstream success, such as alternative rock, metalcore, grunge, thrash metal, emo, and post-hardcore.

Proto-Punk refers to a number of bands which were essential precursors to the Punk movement. Since the term refers to a large group of bands, the characteristics of the subgenre vary from band to band. For the most part, these bands were precursors to Punk because they represented the Punk aesthetic before there technically was a Punk aesthetic. These characteristics include primitive production, amateur sounding composition, DIY aesthetic, etc.

Emo rock is a style of rock music characterized by melodic musicianship and expressive, often confessional lyrics. It originated in the mid-1980s hardcore punk movement of Washington, DC, where it was known as "emotional hardcore" or "emocore" and pioneered by bands such as Rites of Spring and Embrace.

An amalgam of early Rock n Roll, Blues and Country music, Rockabilly's frenzied and visceral beat was usually performed with spare instrumentation that touched on traditional country/folk arrangements.

Psychobilly combined the Rockabilly revival of the late 70s/early 80s with a distinctly Punk aesthetic and attitude; fast rhythms and loud guitars are accompanied by a countrified swing. Psychobilly maintains a lyrical style that usually plays with cultural taboos, exploring topics like violence and sexuality.

f the major influences of hard rock is blues music. considerably harder than conventional rock music. hard rock is loud, aggressive guitar rock, but it isn't as heavy as heavy metal, and it's only very rarely influenced by punk (though it helped inspire punk). Hard rock generally prizes big, stadium-ready guitar riffs, anthemic choruses, and stomping, swaggering backbeats.

Black Metal often employs fast tempos, shrieked vocals, highly distorted guitars played with tremolo picking, double-kick drumming, and unconventional song structure. When composing music, guitarists often use scales, intervals and chord progressions that produce the most dissonant, fearful and ominous sounds. Additionally, guitar solos and low guitar tunings are a rarity in black metal.

Death metal is an extreme subgenre of heavy metal. It typically employs fast tempos, heavily distorted guitars, deep demonic growling vocals, blast beat drumming, and complex song structures with multiple tempo changes.

Doom metal is a form of heavy metal music that typically employs very slow tempos, low-tuned guitars and a much 'thicker' or 'heavier' sound than other metal genres. Both the music and the lyrics intend to evoke a sense of despair, dread, and impending doom.

It combines the aggression of heavy metal with the dark melancholy of gothic rock. The music of gothic metal is diverse with bands known to adopt the gothic approach to different styles of heavy metal music. Lyrics are generally melodramatic and mournful with inspiration from gothic fiction as well as personal experiences.

Grindcore is characterized by heavily distorted, down-tuned guitars, high speed tempo, blast beats, songs often lasting no more than two minutes (some are seconds long), and vocals which consist of growls and high-pitched screams. Lyrical themes range from social and political issues to gore and black humor.
Combines hard-driving heavy metal guitar riffs, the pounding bass rhythms characteristic of funk, and sometimes hip hop-style rhymes into an alternative rock approach to songwriting.

Characterized by most notably heavy riffs but usually with a pronounced experimental edge, including unconventional lyrics, more syncopation than typical metal, unusual technique, a resistance to conventional approaches to heavy music and an incorporation of a wide range of influences outside of the metal music scene.

While pure "industrial" takes its primary cues from experimental music and electronic dance, Industrial Metal makes the distorted noise of electric guitars a crucial part of the music. Ministry was the first band to popularize industrial metal in the late '80s, basing their signature grind on countless repetitions of jackhammer guitar riffs, as well as electronics, samples, and distorted vocals; however, it was Nine Inch Nails that really brought the sound to the mainstream during the early '90s, thanks to Trent Reznor's flair for melodic songwriting and multi-layered production.

Metalcore combines extreme metal with hardcore punk. The most defining characteristic of metalcore is the presence of breakdowns where the music goes into a half-time heavily syncopated groove. These breakdowns are generally the climax of intensity for the song. Blastbeats, and hardcore style double time riffs are also common.

Nu metal is a blend of grunge, alternative metal, and funk metal. Vocals have a range extending from melodic singing, rapping, and guttural screaming, to death growls and shouting. Bass parts are often reminiscent of hip hop or funk grooves, and in some songs, slap bass technique is used to give the music a funk groove.

Progressive metal is a fusion genre; a mixture of progressive rock and heavy metal. Progressive metal blends the powerful, guitar-driven sound of metal with the complex compositional structures, odd time signatures, and intricate instrumental playing of progressive rock. Some progressive metal bands are also influenced by jazz fusion and classical music. Like progressive rock songs, progressive metal songs are usually much longer than standard metal songs, and they are often thematically linked in concept albums.

Described as aggressive and "extremely fast, abrasive, and technically demanding music. Also speed metal eventually toned down its intense tempos and evolved into thrash metal. Two of the most influential bands to the genre were English groups Motrhead and Judas Priest

Stoner rock and stoner metal are interchangeable terms describing sub-genres of rock and metal music. It combines elements of psychedelic rock, blues-rock and doom metal. Stoner rock is typically slow-to-mid tempo and features low-tuned guitars, a bass-heavy sound, melodic vocals, and 'retro' production.

Thrash metal (sometimes referred to simply as thrash), is an extreme subgenre of heavy metal that is characterized by its fast tempo and aggression. Thrash metal songs typically use fast, percussive and low-register guitar riffs, overlaid with shredding-style lead work.[1] Thrash metal lyrics often deal with social issues using direct and denunciatory language, an approach which partially overlaps with the hardcore genre.

Art Rock and Progressive Rock (Prog Rock) are quite similar. Prog Rock, though, tends to be more traditionally melodic (even when multi-sectioned compositions replace normal song structures), and more oriented toward classically trained instrumental technique. Both Art Rock and Prog Rock stem from a mostly British attempt to elevate rock music to new levels of artistic credibility.

Kraut Rock refers to the legions of German bands of the early '70s that expanded the sonic possibilities of art and progressive rock. Working with early synthesizers and splicing together seemingly unconnected reels of tape, bands like Faust, Can, and Neu created a droning, pulsating sound that owed more to the avant garde than to rock & roll.

Noise-Rock is an outgrowth of punk rock, specifically the sort of punk that expressed youthful angst and exuberance through the glorious racket of amateurishly played electric guitars. Most noise-rock bands concentrate on the ear-shattering sounds that can be produced by distorted electric guitars, some also use electronic instrumentation, whether as percussion or to add to an overall cacophony of sound.

Post-rock was the dominant form of experimental rock during the '90s. Post-rock was hypnotic and often droning (especially the guitar- oriented bands), and the brighter-sounding groups were still cool and cerebral -- overall, the antithesis of rock's visceral power.

Art Rock and Progressive Rock are quite similar. Art Rock, though, is more likely to have experimental or avant-garde influences, placing novel sonic texture above prog-rock's symphonic ambitions. Both Art Rock and Progressive rock stem from a mostly British attempt to elevate rock music to new levels of artistic credibility.
Brit Rock refers not to the entire pantheon of British Rock music, but instead a spate of British bands from the late 1980s- early 90s who were influenced by 1960s British Rock, New Wave and Punk.

Although Darkwave can be traced back to the beginnings of Post Punk and Synth Pop, the term was first used in the early 1980's to describe bands of these styles with a noticeably dark sound and lyrics. Darkwave is essentially Post Punk with a gothic sound and lyrics focusing on self-deprecation, angst and drug use.

Far more gritty and less melodic than its Pop Punk counterparts, Garage bands fostered an attitude that was frequently angry, cynical, darkly humorous and violent-- though its early practitioners were more playful. Garage garnered its name thanks to its amateur inclinations both in its live performance and production values. However, it defied geography and significantly influenced mainstream acts of the 1960s and 70s.
A sub-genre whose aesthetic is based as much on fashion as music, Glam Rock's flamboyant hedonism catered to a style that dabbled at once in hard rock and eccentric balladeering.

Gothic rock (also referred to as goth rock or simply goth) is a musical subgenre of alternative rock. Gothic rock bands grew from the strong ties they had to the English punk rock and emerging post-punk scenes. The genre itself was defined as a separate movement from punk rock during the early 1980's largely due to the significant stylistic divergences of the movement; gothic rock, as opposed to punk, combines dark, often keyboard-heavy music with introspective and depressing lyrics.

Grunge has its roots in Punk and Heavy Metal with heavily distorted guitars and lyrical themes of existential angst. Grunge was a reaction to the polished production, overwrought showmanship and fashion of mainstream music in the 1980's. However, in the 1990's Grunge dominated mainstream rock music due to the success of bands like Nirvana and Pearl Jam.

Indie is short for "independent," leading one to assume that Indie Rock is concurrent with the Punk DIY aesthetic. Since Indie Rock is free of the mainstream, it allows bands to experiment and incorporate aspects of underground culture. Since the late 1990's, Indie Rock has grown in popularity with bands signing to corporate record labels and music publishers, thus Indie Rock has become more of a prescription for song composition than a protest against commercialism.

Abrasive and aggressive fusion of rock and electronic music, industrial was initially a blend of avant-garde electronics experiments (tape music, musique concrte, white noise, synthesizers, sequencers, etc.) and punk provocation. It's early forms included mail art, performance art, installation pieces and other art forms.

Though Glam exerted an enormous influence on genres ranging from Punk to Hair Metal, Neo Glam refers to those British bands who-- in the early-to-mid 90s-- attempted to revive the androgynous excess and romanticism of their 70s forebears.

Post Grunge began to surface almost immediately after the commercial success of the Grunge movement. Post Grunge essentially used the Grunge aesthetic as a prescription for song composition-- imitating the Grunge sound, while incorporating mainstream production techniques. The result is a movement created specifically for the spotlight of the 1990's.

Post Punk took the independent, D.I.Y. attitude of Punk and incorporated musical experimentation. This resulted in a more complicated derivative of Punk, with particular attention paid to lyrics and composition. Post Punk paved the way for what would become known as Alternative Rock/Pop music.

A product of the early hardcore punk movement, Post-Hardcore conveys a more expressive and complex means of communicating aggravation and angst. Post-Hardcore utilizes the harsh, guitar-heavy timbres of Hardcore Punk, but expands beyond the fast tempos and three-chord composition.

Influenced by the psychedelic culture of the 1960s, Psychedelic Rock bands sought to expand the possibilities of Rock music by incorporating Eastern musical traditions, unusual effects for instruments and free-form song structures. Psychedelic Rock tends toward a dreamy impressionism in its aesthetic, though many of its practitioners were also attached to a traditional, hard-driving Rock sound.

Pop Punk is an amalgam of Punk and Pop, taking cues from mainstream pop music while playing in a punk style: fast distorted riffs, simple composition and melodies. Lyrics are usually wry, cocky and/or apathetic.

Space rock refers to a new generation of alternative/indie bands that draw from psychedelic rock, ambient music, and -- more often than not -- experimental and avant-garde influences. Space rock is nearly always slow, hypnotic, and otherworldly; it typically favors lengthy, mind- bending sonic explorations over conventional song structures, and vocals sometimes play second fiddle to the shimmering instrumental textures.

When Chicago House producers discovered unique sonic possibilities via realtime modulation of the Roland TB-303 filter section (i.e. resonance and filter cut-off knobs), a term called "acid" was used to describe the squelchy sounds coming from the box and the lively and quirky, mid-tempo House music called Acid House was spawned.

Chicago House typifies the music from or appropriating the sound of 1980s Chicago House music; a sound essentially characterized by an upbeat, pointed, driving and straight while syncopated musical arrangement. Musical motifs include Houses "four to the floor" rhythmic core interplayed by syncopated, lively hi-hat and snare drum patterns (including frequent snare drum roll break downs), simple bass-lines, textured synth pads, thematic synth stabs and arpeggiation. A vocal question and answer technique frequently alternates between a featured R&B vocalist and spoken lyrical motifs, performed either by an emcee or using sampled vocal phrases. Through the 1980s and into the 1990s Chicago House sound evolved into several other House music sub-genres including Deep House and Acid House etc..

Deep House is a relatively laid-back, melancholic, down-tempo House music (110-125 bpm) typified by a hypnotic personality characterized by its continuously evolving motifs sustained over few dynamic shifts. Its characteristically sparse arrangement, often characterized by Jazz chord colors which outline harmonic ostinatos, consists of a small Synthetic Ensemble including simplified drum machine patterns -- often created using softer kick drum sounds -- more subtle, shorter hi-hat patterns and an emphasis on production techniques including reverb, delay, and filter effects.
Disco House fuses quintessential House music form with quintessential melodic & harmonic ingredients of classic anthemic Disco music (i.e. looped disco samples).

Electro house is a synthetic, pointed, robotic, playful, lively and mid to uptempo (i.e. 125 to 140 BPM) fusion dance music subgenre. It stylistically combines minimal, processed "four on the floor" anchored beats commonly found in house and techno, with melodically rich, often abrasive and pointed, analogue or digital basslines & synths logically evolved from tech house. Thematic influences are wide and varied ranging from 1980-s Pop & New Wave, to anthemic Trance-like harmonic progressions, to simplistic bassline structure and beyond.

Sometimes known as Filter House or French Touch to describe the sound and location in which this House music sub- genre originates, French House is quintessentially a groove-oriented, anthemic, mid-tempo House music (i.e. 110-130 bpm) which combines House Music's rhythmic core (i.e. "four-on-the-floor") with either or both filter cut-off & phaser effects and classic Disco samples and/or motifs.

Also known as House Rap, Hip House fuses the rhythmic, harmonic, melodic and production elements of classic Chicago House with Hip-Hop; it is quintessentially classic Rap against a classic House track.

Jazz-House fuses House music's quintessential rhythmic core (i.e. "four on the floor") with Jazz music's harmonic & melodic personality and its distinctive tendency towards improvisation. As a result, Jazz-House tends to sound more varied, sophisticated and improvised.

When New York based Latin-American descended House pioneers paid homage to their heritage by releasing Vocal House records in Spanish, Latin House was born. Latin House fuses House music's quintessential thematic ingredients (i.e. "four on the floor" rhythmic core and anthemic harmonic & melodic arrangements) with distinctive harmonic, melodic and rhythmic undertones of Latin musics originating from Brazil, Puerto Rico, Mexico, Cuba, Dominican Republic, Colombia and Spain.

Implied by its name, Minimal House strips House music down to a sparse, minimal aesthetic; "four on the floor" rhythmic- core interplayed by syncopation in both or either percussion and melody. Minimal House combines thematic characteristics of Tech House, the dark tone color of deep house, the rhythmic anatomy and energy of minimal techno, the thematic (i.e. melodic & harmonic) with the syncopated, sample-oriented production techniques of glitch (i.e. the replacement of quintessential house-oriented rhythmic track samples with glitch-oriented clicks, small bits of static- noises, glitches) to create a unique house music dance genre. Vocals in minimal house are often simplistic, nonsensical and monotone in nature.

Progressive House is an anthemic, dynamic, evolving and hypnotic uptempo (i.e. 128 - 140 BPM) House music sub- genre characteristically defined by three underlying anatomical elements of form typified by Trance music; a build-up (a dynamic or energetic anticipation building sequence of sometimes three to four minutes in length), a break-down (an dynamic or energetic dissipation of the build-up) and a climax (a dynamic or energetic explosion of the build-up). Subtle variations in instrumentation (i.e., increasing and decreasing ensemble participation) anticipates the transition to each subsequent anatomical element. The introductory build-up and ending break-down are similarly related adding a feel of symmetry to the overall anatomical form. Additionally, Progressive House borrows thematic (i.e. melodic, harmonic and rhythmic) ingredients from modern Pop & Dance music sub-genres.

Tech (i.e. "Techno") House is a characteristically mid-tempo House music fusing the minimal sterility of Techno with the soulful thematic colors of House. Tech House is frequently characterized by a synthesis of the production aesthetic of minimal techno (i.e. shorter, deeper, darker kick-drum sounds, smaller, filtered hi-hats and noisier snares) with the dark, soulful, groove-based, minimalistic energetic intensities of Deep House. Occasionally Tech House borrows from the dynamic variation of Progressive House and can include the dirty and/or hollow acid-style synth textures of Acid House.

Tribal House is a drum + percussion-focused House music style which uses sophisticated, syncopated rhythmic drum interplay between the quintessential "four-on-the-floor" kick drum pattern and a variety of contrasting, hand-drum samples. As its name implies, Tribal House is reminiscent of indigenous musical influences of Africa and South America, and accordingly, juxtaposed over-top and in between the dense rhythmic-core, passionate vocal shouts and chanting is frequently used.
Vocal House is the driving, majestic & anthemic, over-the-top juxtaposition of soulful R&B vocals with House musics quintessential four-on-the-floor rhythm core.

Acid Techno developed out of the late 1980s Chicago Acid House scene.. Acid Techno is created in the same exact way Acid house is (i.e. four on the floor) but the difference being is that Techno is repetitive, driving and hypnotic where House has more of a soulful feel and has the potential for vocals.

The term Detroit Techno refers to a style of techno music in the tradition of early (1985-1995) techno recordings from Detroit, Michigan, not necessarily indicating the music's geographic origin. A discriminating trait of Detroit techno is the use of analogue synthesizers and early drum machines particularly the Roland TR-909 for its production and the digital emulation of the characteristic sound of those machines.

Minimal Techno music is basically a thematically-stripped down version of it's older brother Techno. Minimal Techno combines Techno music's quintessential core elements (i.e. "four on the floor" kick) with syncopated embellishments, primarily with filtered percussive sounds, and occasional sweeping filter fx, to introduce variation to the repetition.

Inspired by Detroit Techno, Schranz is an uptempo (150-170 BPM), aggressive, frantic, overwhelmingly repetitive style of European Techno music. Schranz uses massive kick drums, driving percussion and distorted, looping synthesizers to fuse compact rhythmic patterns with harsh, abrasive mechanical-like themes.

Hard Trance developed out of the Hardcore Breakbeat era and blends traditional Trance sounds and structure with harder, driving kick drum patterns. Lead synths still retain their melodic "trance-like" nature and sometimes feature a resonating filtered and sometimes offbeat bass line. The tempo in Hard Trance is usually increased to (145-155 BPM).

Progressive Trance is a mid-tempo, darker dance music (i.e. 130-140 BPM) that is characteristically deeper than its commercial Trance counterpart. Where Trance is focused on euphoric, diatonic progression communicated through Vocal Pop song structure, Progressive Trance's songs are often instrumental and focus on deep, dark ostinatos that evolve over a longer period of time and feature long builds, subtle breakdowns and arpeggiated and gated synths.

Psychedelic/Goa Trance is an evolving, syncopated, distinctive, uptempo dance music (generally between 140 and 150 BPM) that features a driving four on the floor kick drum pattern and often uses arpeggiated 16th or 32nd notes. A typical GOA track will generally build up to a much more energetic movement in the second half of the track and then taper off fairly quickly toward the end. Generally 8-12 minutes long, Goa tracks usually have a noticeably stronger bassline than other forms of Trance music and incorporates more organic "squelchy" sounds. GOA is usually hypnotic, evolving and psychedelic hence the name and sometimes incorporates middle eastern samples..

Digital Hardcore music is typically a high-tempo, abrasive piercing and distorted punk rock dance music combining the speed, heaviness and attitude of hardcore punk, riot grrrl and Industrial Rock with Hardcore Techno and Jungle. Some bands such as Atari Teenage Riot incorporate elements from hip-hop music including freestyle rap. The use of electric guitar is typical it is played in conjunction with samplers, synthesizers and drum machines, and occasionally supported by traditional electric bass guitars and acoustic drum kits. Vocals are more often shouted than sung by more than one member of the group.

Gabba (a.k.a Gabber) is a form of Hardcore Techno; it is a driving, aggressive, and frantic uptempo dance music (i.e. 160 to 220 BPM). Gabba usually has either a scary or a happy mood. Gabba's vocal delivery contrasts with Happy Hardcore, Gabba vocal delivery is aggressive and rough whereas Happy Hardcore vocal delivery is sentimental and dreamy. Characteristically, Gabba has a loud and often aggressive sound consisting of a driving and wildly distorted "four on the floor" Roland TR-909 kick drum pattern, often overdriven to the point where it becomes a square wave and makes a recognizably melodic tone. Another component of Gabber is the"Hoover" which is typically a distorted, grainy, sweeping sound which when played on a low key can create a dark and brooding bass line. Alternatively, when played at higher pitches the hoover becomes an aggressive, shrieking lead. Faster gabber tracks often apply extremely fast hoover- patterns.

Closely related to Gabba, Happy Hardcore is characterized as a driving, "four on the floor", happy uptempo dance music (i.e. 160180 BPM). What distinguishes it from Gabba is its extremely quirky and happy emotional energy paired with solo vocals which are most often cheerful and sometimes dreamy as well as sentimental.

Big Beat is a sub genre of Breakbeat and is characterized as distorted, compressed breakbeats at moderate tempos (i.e. 120 to 140 BPM), Acid House-style synthesizer lines and heavy loops from 60s and 70s funk, jazz, rock, and pop songs. They are often punctuated with punk-style vocals but is not a requirement and driven by intense, distorted basslines. Other elements of Big Beat includes crescendos, builds, drops, dramatic sound effects, such as explosions or sirens, and extended drum rolls. As with several other dance genres at the time, the use of effects such as cut-off, phasing, and flanging was commonplace.

Inspired by Jungle music, Drill N Bass is an uptempo breakbeat Electronic Dance Music defined by its extremely frantic, hard, aggressive, pointed, intricate, syncopated and complex drum programming (i.e. often sampled, or influenced by the famous "Amen" breakbeat) combined with abstract, mechanical, spherical and often pointed and syncopated synthesizer-based ingredients which outline a minimal harmonic and melodic structure.

Evolving from Jungle and Breakbeat Hardcore, Drum N Bass is characterized as a driving, uptempo (i.e.150-190 BPM), often Jazz & Soul influenced, breaktbeat-focused Electronic Dance Music. Percussion focuses on intricate and complex, pointed breakbeat drum sequencing coupled with fat, powerful basslines. Melodic elements are similarly complexly sequenced and usually feature many effects. Vocals are relatively uncommon although often reminiscent of the soulful vocal elements of House music. Drum N Bass are generally less complex (i.e. fast while more repetitive) than the chopped breakbeats of Jungle.

Originating in South London, Dubstep fuses Hip Hop, Two Step, Dub Reggae (and occasionally Drum n Bass) to create a dark, halftime- feel uptempo (i.e. 140 BPM), Electronic Dance Music, Dubstep's sound is identified by it's trademark wobble bass line (created by modulating the filter cutoff and envelope attack) juxtaposed against a drum pattern that includes a straight ahead kick drum pattern frequently syncopated in turnarounds. Crafted with build ups and breakdowns, Dubstep is mostly instrumental however it does make use of vocal techniques such as Sinjaying, Grime (i.e. style of British Rap) or R&B oriented singing.

EBM (a.k.a. as Electronic Body Music) is the fusion of Electronic Dance and Industrial. More beat and melodic driven then Industrial, EBM is a characterized as a lively, dark, synthetic, mechanical and mid-tempo (i.e. 128 BPM) Electronic Dance Music. EBM uses either a "four on the floor" or rock-drum syncopated kick drum pattern fused with a bright, repetitive, arpeggiating synthesizers and frequently features dark, talk-singing, growled or shouted Vocals.

Electro (i.e. electronic), other wise known as Electro-funk, was named via the 1980s UK music scene and described the pointed while heavily groove-centric, syncopated and synthetic African-American Electronic Dance music. Electro is defined by its use of thick and rich synthetic instrumentation created from a heavy use of analogue drum machines (i.e. TR-808) and analogue synthesizers (i.e. Moog). Electro's drum patterns lean towards, mechanical, sequenced and electronic emulations of Funk music's drum-set focused grooves (i.e. breakbeats) and are outlined by a syncopated kick drum pattern and a snare or clap accented offbeat. Vocals are sparse and often processed with either distortion or vocoder.

Generally acknowledged to be the predecessor of Drum N Bass, Jungle is an uptempo, (i.e. 150-170 BPM) pointed, syncopated, mystic, evolving while minimal (in ensemble elements), dub reggae and dancehall influenced, breakbeat Electronic Dance Music. Typically, Jungle is comprised of a frantic fast breakbeat -- frequently referencing the famous "Amen" breakbeat -- and/or frequently defined by a lively, high-pass filtered syncopated, hi-hat and snare break. Through filtering or the use of alternate loops or samples breakbeats are varied over the course of song's development and paired with a slower syncopated, sine-wave focused reggae dub/dancehall influenced bass line (i.e. a tuned 808 kick) rhythmically matched with a kick drum (i.e. often a punchy, filtered acoustic kick drum sample). Additionally, mystic elements are communicated through the use of melodic instruments such as synthesizers and keyboards. The frequent use of Ragga and Reggae vocals and Jungle's tendency towards traditional groove-oriented breakbeats differentiates Drum n Bass from Jungle.

A descendant of House music which originated in the UK, UK Garage is a lively, mid-tempo, pointed, syncopated, and groove-based Broken-Beat focused Electronic Dance music. UK Garage quintessentially features a distinctive syncopated, hi-pass filtered Broken Beat which interplays with a syncopated dub-style synth bass, frequently combined with "chopped up" and time or pitch-shifted vocal samples and a pop sensibility-focused song structure. The defining musical elements of Garage were largely absorbed into other sub-genres in the mid-2000s, including Grime, UK Funky, Dubstep and Bassline.

Ambient is form of electronic music that puts more emphasis on actual texture, atmosphere and mood which is hypnotic, dreamy as well as spherical with the help of conventional and unconventional instruments, sound clips, and sometimes vocal clips. Singing in Ambient music can be done, although a good deal of Ambient is instrumental.

Downtempo is a laid-back, dreamy, spherical and hypnotic style of electronic music similar to Ambient music but usually with a beat or groove. Downtempo is made up of hypnotic drum loops and always has a laid-back style. It tends to be more groove/beat-driven than ambient music but slower than trip-hop and can often be instrumental.

Dub (electro) or Dubtronica consists of electronic beats played in a downbeat manner. It is much slower in speed than techno and generally warmer than dance-oriented electronica. The genre is highly influenced by "Dub" (i.e. a Reggae sub genre) and is repetitive and some tracks use reggae toasters or singers to produce a more accessible form of the music.

Electronica/Eclectic is an umbrella term used to describe the emergence of Electronic Dance Music increasingly geared to listening instead of strictly dancing (i.e. Post Club Music), Electronica is normally considered more intelligent than dance music. The music is more about using technology to create unusual sounds, melodies and heavily processed drums (often in patterns where the same bar is never repeated requiring painstaking programming). These elements are crafted into an intricate and some times emotive piece of music. The results are usually closer ambient and experimental music than they are to dance music.

Glitch is a style of experimental Electronic Music that uses the sounds created by malfunctioning digital technology - bugs, crashes, system errors, hardware noise, CD skipping, and digital distortion - to create a composition. Glitch is characterized as pointed, robotic, mechanical and somewhat nervous/hectic. Modern glitch tends to use software to recreate these sounds, as opposed to genuinely defecting technology and this increased ease of creation has resulted in the genre spreading out into other areas, such as Glitch Pop and Glitch Hop.

Intelligent Dance Music (commonly referred to as IDM) describes a broad range of post-rave sounds. The sound emerged as DJs started to make music more suited for the headphones than the dance floor. The irony of the name is that the majority is not, in fact, dance music, but music instead better suited for home listening. Over the late 90s, IDM morphed into the primary genre for electronic experimentation with elements of glitch and noise predominating the sounds of many of its innovators, such as Aphex Twin and Autechre.

Trip-Hop is a style of "Downtempo" that fuses Hip Hop, R&B, Jazz and Electronic music. While Trip Hop shares the constant and repetitive beats of Downtempo, Trip Hop is texturally a little more busy often using a wide array of samples of both live and electronic instrumentals with at times turntable scratches and vocal melodies and almost always maintaining a mellow tempo. The beats often invoke a surreal, hypnotic, dreamy and yet slightly dark atmosphere. One of the most distinguishing features of Trip Hop are the vocals which include various styles like R&B and Jazz.

Electroclash is a style of Electronic Music that fuses New Wave, Punk, Synth Pop & Electronic Dance Music. The movement combines this 1980s sound (using synthesizers, drum machines, etc) The name derives from the Electropop bands who provide the majority of the musical influence. Lyrics are generally punk inspired and more given to emotion than technique while the vocals are generally atonal in nature.

Indietronic is a short term for Electronic Indie Music. It's the electronic variant of Indie Rock/Pop. Typical instruments used in Indietronica are electronic keyboard, synthesizer, sampler and drum machines as well as bass guitar and electric guitar. During the early 2000s, the number of indie electronic artists grew exponentially as home recording and software synthesizers (or softsynths) became common.
Neo Disco updates the classic Disco sound with flourishes of Electronic Dance Music.
